## 1. The Recommender Mindset

Every recommender system in SQL answers one question:

> **"Given what we know about user X, what item should we surface next?"**

There are three strategies, and real systems blend all three:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                   RECOMMENDATION STRATEGIES                     │
├─────────────────┬───────────────────────────┬───────────────────┤
│  Collaborative  │     Content-Based         │  Hybrid / Rules   │
│  Filtering      │     Filtering             │                   │
├─────────────────┼───────────────────────────┼───────────────────┤
│ User-based:     │ Match item attributes     │ Popularity        │
│ similar users   │ to user profile           │ fallback          │
│ → same items    │                           │                   │
│                 │ e.g. "You like action     │ Category affinity │
│ Item-based:     │ movies → here are more    │                   │
│ similar items   │ action movies"            │ Session-based     │
│ → next purchase │                           │ (real-time)       │
└─────────────────┴───────────────────────────┴───────────────────┘
```

**Why item-item >> user-user at FAANG scale:**
- User-user: compare every user to every other user → O(N²) pairs. With 1B users, this is impossible in real time.
- Item-item: item similarities are pre-computed offline and stored. At query time, just look up the items the user has interacted with → fetch pre-computed similar items. O(1) online.

**The cold-start problem:**
- New user: no interaction history → fall back to popularity/trending.
- New item: no co-purchase data → fall back to content-based (category, attributes).

