## 2. The Four Similarity Metrics

Before writing any query, understand what metric to use and why.

### Jaccard Similarity

```
Jaccard(A, B) = |A ∩ B| / |A ∪ B|
             = co_count / (count_a + count_b - co_count)
```

**Use when:** binary data (bought / not bought, liked / not liked). Penalizes popular items naturally — two niche items with 3 co-purchases out of 5 total are more similar than two popular items with 100 co-purchases out of 10,000.

**Range:** 0 (no overlap) to 1 (identical sets).

### Lift

```
Lift(A → B) = P(A and B) / (P(A) × P(B))
            = (co_count × total_orders) / (count_a × count_b)
```

**Use when:** you want to measure how much MORE likely two items are to be bought together versus by random chance. Lift = 1 means independence. Lift > 1 means positive association.

**Intuition:** If milk appears in 50% of baskets and bread in 40%, you'd expect them together in 20% of baskets by chance. If they appear together in 40%, lift = 40/20 = 2.

### Confidence

```
Confidence(A → B) = P(A and B) / P(A)
                  = co_count / count_a
```

**Use when:** directional rules ("if user buys A, show them B"). Confidence tells you: of all the times A was bought, how often was B also bought?

**Caveat:** Confidence ignores B's popularity. If B is in 99% of all baskets, confidence is trivially high. Always pair with lift.

### Cosine Similarity

```
Cosine(A, B) = dot_product(A, B) / (norm(A) × norm(B))
             = Σ(score_a × score_b) / (√Σscore_a² × √Σscore_b²)
```

**Use when:** weighted/continuous data (view counts, ratings, implicit feedback scores). Two users who both rated the same movies similarly will have a high cosine — even if one is a light user and one is heavy, because cosine normalizes by magnitude.

**Range:** 0 to 1 (with non-negative scores).

