## 3. Item-Item Collaborative Filtering (Co-Purchase)

**"Users who bought X also bought Y."** — The Amazon sidebar.

### The Core Join Pattern

The trick is a **self-join on `order_id`** — the same order contains both items:

```sql
FROM orders a
JOIN orders b
  ON  a.order_id   = b.order_id     -- same basket
  AND a.product_id < b.product_id   -- canonical pair, no duplicates
```

### Full Query with Jaccard + Lift

```sql
-- Step 1: Find all co-purchased pairs + count
WITH co_purchases AS (
  SELECT
    a.product_id                   AS product_a,
    b.product_id                   AS product_b,
    COUNT(DISTINCT a.order_id)     AS co_purchase_count
  FROM orders a
  JOIN orders b
    ON  a.order_id   = b.order_id
    AND a.product_id < b.product_id
  GROUP BY a.product_id, b.product_id
),
-- Step 2: Individual product purchase counts
product_counts AS (
  SELECT product_id,
    COUNT(DISTINCT order_id) AS total_orders
  FROM orders
  GROUP BY product_id
),
-- Step 3: Total orders in the catalog (for lift denominator)
total AS (
  SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT order_id) AS n FROM orders
)
SELECT
  cp.product_a,
  cp.product_b,
  cp.co_purchase_count,
  pa.total_orders                                           AS orders_a,
  pb.total_orders                                           AS orders_b,
  -- Jaccard: co_count / union
  ROUND(cp.co_purchase_count * 1.0 /
    (pa.total_orders + pb.total_orders - cp.co_purchase_count), 4)
    AS jaccard_similarity,
  -- Lift: (co_count × total) / (count_a × count_b)
  ROUND(cp.co_purchase_count * 1.0 * t.n /
    (pa.total_orders * pb.total_orders), 4)
    AS lift,
  -- Confidence A→B
  ROUND(cp.co_purchase_count * 1.0 / pa.total_orders, 4)  AS confidence_a_to_b,
  -- Confidence B→A
  ROUND(cp.co_purchase_count * 1.0 / pb.total_orders, 4)  AS confidence_b_to_a
FROM co_purchases cp
JOIN product_counts pa ON cp.product_a = pa.product_id
JOIN product_counts pb ON cp.product_b = pb.product_id
CROSS JOIN total t
ORDER BY lift DESC;
```

### CTE-Level I/O Trace

**Input `orders`:**
```
order_id | user_id | product_id
O1       | U1      | P1
O1       | U1      | P2
O1       | U1      | P3
O2       | U2      | P1
O2       | U2      | P2
O3       | U3      | P2
O3       | U3      | P3
```

**`co_purchases` — self-join on order_id, product_a < product_b:**

Pairs from O1: (P1,P2), (P1,P3), (P2,P3)
Pairs from O2: (P1,P2)
Pairs from O3: (P2,P3)

```
product_a | product_b | co_purchase_count
P1        | P2        | 2   (O1 and O2)
P1        | P3        | 1   (O1 only)
P2        | P3        | 2   (O1 and O3)
```

**`product_counts`:**
```
product_id | total_orders
P1         | 2   (O1, O2)
P2         | 3   (O1, O2, O3)
P3         | 2   (O1, O3)
```

**`total`:** n = 3 orders

**Final metrics for (P1, P2):**
```
co_count   = 2
orders_a   = 2  (P1)
orders_b   = 3  (P2)
jaccard    = 2 / (2 + 3 - 2)    = 2/3  = 0.6667
lift       = (2 × 3) / (2 × 3)  = 6/6  = 1.0000
conf_a→b   = 2/2 = 1.0000  (every P1 order also had P2)
conf_b→a   = 2/3 = 0.6667  (2/3 P2 orders also had P1)
```

**For (P2, P3):**
```
jaccard    = 2 / (3 + 2 - 2) = 2/3 = 0.6667
lift       = (2 × 3) / (3 × 2) = 1.0000
conf_a→b   = 2/3 = 0.6667
```

**Output:**
```
product_a | product_b | co_count | jaccard | lift   | conf_a→b | conf_b→a
P1        | P2        | 2        | 0.6667  | 1.0000 | 1.0000   | 0.6667
P2        | P3        | 2        | 0.6667  | 1.0000 | 0.6667   | 1.0000
P1        | P3        | 1        | 0.3333  | 1.0000 | 0.5000   | 0.5000
```

> **Why does lift = 1.0 here?** With only 3 orders and these specific co-occurrences, the expected and actual co-purchase rates are equal. In real data, niche item pairs will have lift >> 1.

