## 6. User-Based Collaborative Filtering (Cosine / Implicit Feedback)

**When users have weighted interactions** (views, cart adds, purchases), Jaccard ignores signal strength. Cosine similarity captures it.

```sql
-- Step 1: Build weighted interaction scores per user-product
WITH weighted AS (
  SELECT user_id, product_id,
    SUM(CASE
      WHEN event_type = 'purchase'    THEN 10
      WHEN event_type = 'add_to_cart' THEN 3
      WHEN event_type = 'view'        THEN 1
      ELSE 0
    END) AS score
  FROM events
  GROUP BY user_id, product_id
),
-- Step 2: For each user pair, compute dot product and norms
similarity AS (
  SELECT
    a.user_id AS user_a,
    b.user_id AS user_b,
    SUM(a.score * b.score)         AS dot_product,  -- Σ(score_a × score_b)
    SQRT(SUM(POW(a.score, 2)))     AS norm_a,        -- √(Σ score_a²)
    SQRT(SUM(POW(b.score, 2)))     AS norm_b         -- √(Σ score_b²)
  FROM weighted a
  JOIN weighted b
    ON  a.product_id = b.product_id   -- same product (aligned dimensions)
    AND a.user_id    < b.user_id
  GROUP BY a.user_id, b.user_id
)
SELECT
  user_a,
  user_b,
  dot_product,
  ROUND(norm_a, 4) AS norm_a,
  ROUND(norm_b, 4) AS norm_b,
  ROUND(dot_product / NULLIF(norm_a * norm_b, 0), 4) AS cosine_similarity
FROM similarity
ORDER BY cosine_similarity DESC;
```

### CTE-Level I/O Trace

**Input `events`:**
```
user_id | product_id | event_type
U1      | P1         | purchase      (+10)
U1      | P1         | view          (+1)
U1      | P2         | add_to_cart   (+3)
U2      | P1         | purchase      (+10)
U2      | P2         | purchase      (+10)
```

**`weighted`:**
```
user_id | product_id | score
U1      | P1         | 11   (10 + 1)
U1      | P2         | 3    (3)
U2      | P1         | 10
U2      | P2         | 10
```

**`similarity`** — join U1 × U2 on shared products (P1 and P2):

```
Product P1: a.score=11, b.score=10 → dot contribution = 110
Product P2: a.score=3,  b.score=10 → dot contribution = 30

dot_product = 110 + 30 = 140
norm_a = √(11² + 3²)  = √(121 + 9)  = √130 ≈ 11.402
norm_b = √(10² + 10²) = √200        ≈ 14.142
cosine = 140 / (11.402 × 14.142)   ≈ 140 / 161.24 ≈ 0.8682
```

**Output:**
```
user_a | user_b | dot_product | norm_a  | norm_b  | cosine_similarity
U1     | U2     | 140         | 11.4018 | 14.1421 | 0.8682
```

> **Why not Jaccard here?** Jaccard would say U1 and U2 have Jaccard = 2/(2+2-2) = 1.0 — perfect similarity. But U2 has 10 purchase score on P2 while U1 only has 3 (cart add). Cosine captures that U2 is more committed to P2 than U1 — a meaningful distinction for recommending P2 to U1.

