## 9. Popularity-Based Fallback (Cold Start)

**For new users with no history — rank everything by trending score.**

```sql
WITH product_stats AS (
  SELECT
    product_id,
    COUNT(DISTINCT order_id)   AS purchase_count,
    COUNT(DISTINCT user_id)    AS unique_buyers,
    SUM(amount)                AS total_revenue,
    -- Recency buckets
    SUM(CASE WHEN order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL 7  DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)  AS purchases_7d,
    SUM(CASE WHEN order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL 30 DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)  AS purchases_30d,
    SUM(CASE WHEN order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL 90 DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)  AS purchases_90d
  FROM orders
  GROUP BY product_id
)
SELECT
  product_id,
  purchase_count,
  unique_buyers,
  total_revenue,
  purchases_7d,
  purchases_30d,
  -- Trending score: heavier weight on recent purchases
  ROUND(
    purchases_7d  * 0.50 +
    purchases_30d * 0.30 +
    unique_buyers * 0.20
  , 2)                                              AS trending_score,
  RANK() OVER (ORDER BY purchases_7d   DESC)        AS trending_rank,
  RANK() OVER (ORDER BY purchase_count DESC)        AS all_time_rank,
  RANK() OVER (ORDER BY unique_buyers  DESC)        AS reach_rank
FROM product_stats
ORDER BY trending_score DESC
LIMIT 50;
```

### I/O Trace

```
product | p_count | unique_buyers | p_7d | p_30d | trending_score
P1      | 500     | 300           | 100  | 200   | 100×0.5 + 200×0.3 + 300×0.2 = 50+60+60 = 170
P2      | 1000    | 100           | 10   | 50    | 10×0.5  + 50×0.3  + 100×0.2 = 5+15+20  = 40
```

P1 wins trending despite fewer all-time purchases — it's heating up recently.

