## 14. Trending Score — Recency-Weighted Popularity

**"Surface what's hot right now, not just what sold well historically."**

```sql
WITH product_stats AS (
  SELECT
    o.product_id,
    p.name,
    p.category,
    COUNT(DISTINCT o.order_id)  AS all_time_purchases,
    COUNT(DISTINCT o.user_id)   AS unique_buyers,
    SUM(o.amount)               AS total_revenue,
    SUM(CASE WHEN o.order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL  7 DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS p_7d,
    SUM(CASE WHEN o.order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL 30 DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS p_30d,
    SUM(CASE WHEN o.order_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL 90 DAY
             THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS p_90d
  FROM orders o
  JOIN products p ON o.product_id = p.product_id
  GROUP BY o.product_id, p.name, p.category
)
SELECT
  product_id, name, category,
  all_time_purchases, unique_buyers,
  p_7d, p_30d, p_90d,
  ROUND(
    p_7d  * 0.50 +   -- last 7d weighted heaviest (most recent signal)
    p_30d * 0.30 +   -- last 30d moderate weight
    unique_buyers * 0.20  -- reach as a quality signal
  , 2)                                             AS trending_score,
  RANK() OVER (ORDER BY p_7d DESC)                AS trending_rank_7d,
  RANK() OVER (ORDER BY all_time_purchases DESC)   AS all_time_rank,
  RANK() OVER (
    PARTITION BY category ORDER BY p_7d DESC
  )                                                AS trending_rank_in_category
FROM product_stats
ORDER BY trending_score DESC
LIMIT 50;
```

### Why Partition the Rank by Category?

`trending_rank_in_category` lets you build category-specific trending carousels ("Trending in Electronics") while the global `trending_score` powers the homepage. You compute both in one pass.

